{
  "doc_id": "57587",
  "text": "While our model recapitulates many of the risk factors associated with susceptibility to AN, [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] there are two notable differences-lack of chronicity of self-imposed CR and diminished gender preference. During an AE in mice, food intake is suppressed by more than 80%. Thus, mice that maintain AEs for 3 days do not survive. Because the degree of food intake restriction is less severe in humans, this behavior can be maintained over a long period of time. It has been proposed that dieting and weight loss become a rewarding habit in some individuals, which fosters the persistence of this self-destructive behavior. [CITATION_7] Our observations are consistent with the idea that circuits responsible for triggering restrictive feeding behavior may be distinct from those that maintain it over a long period of time. If true, addressing both aspects of the pathological behavior may be needed to develop efficacious treatments for AN.",
